R614 – This rule has been updated to allow COTS Power-over-Ethernet injectors (i.e. 802.3af, at, or bt devices) when used with COTS receiving devices (i.e. not breakout or adapters).

Just trying to clarify my understanding, does this finally allow for higher voltage if industry standard PoE is being used or does the 24V limit still apply?

My assumption is that the 24V limit is still implied but it allows for active POE. No risk to accidentally plug a Ethernet cable to a device that doesn’t support POE.

If I am correct, if you plug a active POE device to a non POE device, that is completely fine since the protocol allows communication to request if voltage is needed.
Passive will just give you straight voltage

TFM110:

If I am correct, if you plug a active POE device to a non POE device, that is completely fine since the protocol allows communication to request if voltage is needed.
Passive will just give you straight voltage

That’s why I’ve been asking FIRST to allow industry standard active PoE for ages. “Passive” PoE isn’t even real PoE, there’s no standard for it, and like you said, it kills NICs that don’t expect power to be applied. I’ve seen many students kill the Ethernet port on their own laptops because of this, it’s pretty ridiculous.

At least now we can start to put that firmly in the past.

I really hope the radio is quickly reworked to provide active 802.3af/at PoE, rather than battery passthrough voltage passive PoE.

Your assumption would again be a non-standard af, at, bt implementation is my understanding (like today’s passive POE).

If a standard implementation is allowed (which I’m hoping is what is meant by the blog as it would open up FRC to the majority of industry standardized parts), I believe power delivery is in the range of 40-58V DC.

This makes sense for Ethernet powered devices as the wire gauge is so small in the twisted pairs, to get efficient power delivery you need to up the voltage and lower the current to lower i2c losses in the cable.

I think this is an excellent Q&A question from OP for clarification. The blog post mentioned the PSE and PD (power supply equipment and powered devices respectively), needed to be COTS. This opens the door to an exemption being allowed the standard implementation at a higher voltage than 24v limit otherwise specified. I hope that is the case.
